election_record.label: Ohio 1824 Electoral College

overview.note: Ohio elected 16 electors for Henry Clay, but when the election ended up in the House of Representatives and Henry Clay was no longer one of the candidates, the Congressional Delegation voted for John Quincy Adams.

While the final vote tallies were available by individual elector, almost all other results listed only vote totals by Presidential candidate, and did not differentiate any potential vote differential among the individual electors.
The United States Gazette (Philadelphia, PA) lists Philip Gunkle as an Elector for Andrew Jackson, rather than John Devor.

"A number of the members of the Legislature of Ohio, met in the hall of the house of representatives at Columbus, on the 3d ult. for the purpose of nominating a person to succeed James Monroe, as president of the United States. After the transaction of some preliminary business, several members withdrew, deeming it expedient to make a nomination at that time, when a ballot was had, and the votes stud thus: Henry Clay, 50 votes, DeWitt Clinton, 5 votes, J. Q. Adams, 1 vote, J. C. Calhoun, 1 vote." The Westmoreland Republican (Greensburgh, PA). January 17, 1823.

"The members of the legislature, at a meeting this evening, nominated Mr. Clay as a proper person for the Presidency of the United States, 50 votes to 7 ... The debates at the meeting were long and tedious, and many went away before the final vote was taken." Franklin Gazette (for the Country) (Philadelphia, PA). January 22, 1823.

"These results do not look much like a verification of the prediction of the editor of the Ohio Monitor, who prophecied, a few weeks ago, that Mr. Clay's friends would find themselves in a 'minority of one-eighth, on the reserve'." Cleaveland Herald (Cleveland, OH). November 5, 1824.

"Since our last we have received information, of a late date, from the counties of Columbiana, Wayne, Knox, Richland, Fairfield, Ross, Highland, Lawrence, Scioto, Preble, Dark and Miami, which is highly gratifying to the friends and supporters of General Jackson. His cause is advancing and his popularity increasing, in all these counties with a force and rapidity which leaves no doubt that he will receive the Electoral votes of Ohio, by a glorious and triumphant majority." National Republican and Ohio Political Register (Cincinnati, OH). October 22, 1824.

"The intriguing politicians who calculated, by their arts and cunning, to speculate upon the loaves and fishes of office, already begin to feel the power of the popular voice, and must yield to the supreme constitutional authority of the nation. They see the PEOPLE are detemined to make JACKSON President, and JOHN C. CALHOUN Vice President, and that any longer resistance to the SOVEREIGN WILL must be hopeless and ruinous." National Republican. November 2, 1824.

"The subjoined returns from twelve counties were received principally by the last southern mail, by which it appears JACKSON has received nine thousand seven hundred and fifty six votes: being a majority of 5058 over Clay, 5690 over Adams and near 1000 over both! This fact, causes us to think that the Jackson Ticket will triumph in this state by a majority highly respectable." Hamilton Intelligencer and Advertiser (Hamilton, OH). November 8, 1824.

sub_unit.name: Cincinnati
sub_unit.note: "Owing to the limited provisions of the statute regulating elections, the polls could not be kept open but ten hours, which was not sufficient time to take in all the ballots offered, and examine the qualifications of such voters as were challenged. Had sufficient time been given, there is no doubt from 2300 to 2400 votes would have been taken, as there were nearly 200 voters on the ground when the polls were closed that did not and could not get up to the ballot box. Of those who did not vote, it may be fairly estimated, 200 were for Jackson, 100 for Adams, 50 for Clay." National Republican and Ohio Political Register (Cincinnati, OH). November 2, 1824.
